04622nam a22007815i 9780228017707DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280177077 a10.1515/97802280177072doi  a(DE-B1597)656922  a(OCoLC)1350357010  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRB127.5.C48bE54 2023 7aHEA0180002bisacsh04a616/.04722231 aEngle, Karen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChronic Conditions /cKaren Engle. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b12 illustrations, colour section  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tOn Being Ill and Otherwise Healthy -- tTelling Stories, Chronically -- tFoot Notes -- tJaws -- tSpin Cycles -- tThe Waves -- tOf Spirits and Floods -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations -- tNotes -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImagine a house whose wiring is spliced and patchy with knob and tube, coiled like a serpent ready to strike and spark at any moment. Even if you have a fire trap behind your walls, the lights will turn on. In her memoir of a life lived in physical pain, Karen Engle asks whether and how language can capture what it’s like to be in a body that appears to work from the outside, when its internal systems operate through an ad hoc assemblage of garbled messaging, reroutings, and shaky foundations. A series of narrative reflections capture the myriad ways in which the chronic conditions its suffering subject. Contrary to claims that pain obliterates language – long a trope of writing about illness – Engle contends that the person with chronic pain is not hampered by a scarcity of language, but rather its excess: enervation by the unending waves of utterance. From a history of the word chronic and its shifting significance to meditations on multiple diagnoses and interactions with medical personnel, Chronic Conditions is a doctor’s case file through the looking glass of a creative writer, scholar, and patient. Engle explores, through medical research, literature, and art, how it feels to become attuned to the rhythms of perpetual and mysterious physical pain. At stake here is the search for a kind of writing that does not instrumentalize pain for allegorical or transcendental purposes. Chronic pain is not a sign of weakness, nor is it an opportunity for personal growth, Engle argues. Instead, it is entirely ordinary and deeply affecting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChronic painxPhilosophy. 0aChronic painxPsychological aspects. 0aChronic pain. 0aPain in art. 0aPain in literature. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Physical Impairments.2bisacsh  aart.  abody.  acreative.  adisorder.  afibromyalgia.  ahistory.  ainvisibility.  alanguage.  aliterature.  amedicine.  amemory.  anon-fiction.  apain.  atemporomandibular.  atreatment.  avertigo.  avisual.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228017707?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228017707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228017707/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles